{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584953"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:00:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:00:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14840"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14840"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.19,0.06,0.13,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65791"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14840"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51231"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7879"},{"type":"tags","id":"7880"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"},{"type":"tags","id":"10703"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18550"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65791"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EActivated protein C is an important natural anticoagulant that helps regulate blood clotting. Some individuals have an inherited resistance to its effects, leading to increased thrombotic risk.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the gene most commonly mutated in inherited activated protein C resistance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Factor V gene","Protein C gene","Protein S gene","Antithrombin gene","Prothrombin gene"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor V gene\u003C/strong\u003E contains the most common mutation causing activated protein C resistance. A single point mutation (G1691A) results in Factor V Leiden, where Factor Va becomes resistant to degradation by activated protein C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtein C gene\u003C/strong\u003E mutations cause protein C deficiency, not resistance to its activated form\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtein S gene\u003C/strong\u003E mutations cause protein S deficiency, which reduces activated protein C function but does not cause resistance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntithrombin gene\u003C/strong\u003E mutations cause antithrombin deficiency, affecting a different anticoagulant pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProthrombin gene\u003C/strong\u003E mutations (G20210A) increase prothrombin levels but do not affect activated protein C function\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFactor V Leiden is the most common inherited thrombophilia in populations of European descent, present in about 5% of Caucasians. The mutation increases thrombotic risk by preventing normal degradation of Factor Va by activated protein C.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Factor V Leiden is caused by a specific point mutation (G1691A) in the Factor V gene that makes it resistant to inactivation by activated protein C.","Factor V Leiden is the most common inherited thrombophilia, increasing risk of venous thrombosis 3-7 fold in heterozygotes.","Activated protein C normally acts as an anticoagulant by inactivating Factors Va and VIIIa."],"references":["Kitchens, C. S., Konkle, B. A., \u0026 Kessler, C. M. (2013). Consultative Hemostasis and Thrombosis: Expert Consult-Online and Print. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kujovich JL. Factor V Leiden thrombophilia. Genet Med. 2011 Jan;13(1):1-16. doi: 10.1097/GIM.0b013e3181faa0f2. PMID: 21116184.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51231"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14840"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51231"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T21:51:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-26T21:59:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7531"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65791"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":nu